        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>1) spw0 &amp; spw1 in "Narrow Band" (NB) mode will allow us to investigate the inner part of the circumstellar envelope of O Ceti through the excited H2O maser lines at 321 and 325 GHz. These lines location and spectral characteristics will be compared with the 22-GHz H2O maser line and the OH flaring maser line and location. In consequence, astrometry and spectral resolution are both important. 

2) spw2 &amp; spw3 in "Wide Band" (WB) mode will allow us to detect the stars of the binary system and calibrate the NB dataset by bandpass transfer (and interpolation).

The spectrum in the 321-GHz line from Menten et al (1991) spreads over ~5 km/s, so in order to sample the spectra over a reasonable number of channels we request a spectral resolution of 0.2 km/s.

The sensitivity requested will allow a mas accuracy for the strongest maser spots at the 325-GHz line peak, and 26~mas for the weakest 5 sigma maser spots.

We are aware that the 325-GHz spectral region is affected by the atmosphere but Cycle 0 and CSV results show that the sensitivities
given in the Calculator are reasonable and that requested astrometry can be achieved providing the current bandpass correction best practices are followed.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
