    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>In November 2009, after another 10 years of non-emissivity, o Ceti (Mira A) showed a new outburst in the 1665 MHz OH maser line, which is active until now. Our astrometric EVN map of this outburst, obtained around the OH maximum in February 2010 locates the eruptive zone at a projected distance of 0.2" East of o Ceti, that is on the same side as Mira B. Regular monitoring of the OH and H2O masers shows that both maser species emit over a similar velocity range. This suggests that the OH maser emission emanates from a region relatively close to the star, where OH molecules should not normally be present. We propose to use ALMA Cycle 2 in the most extended configuration to map the H2O shell in the 321- and 325-GHz water masers lines to probe its radial symmetry. If the UV flux from the companion, Mira B, possibly a white dwarf, impacts the shell of Mira A by enhancing H2O dissociation, we expect absence of H2O maser emission in the part of the shell facing Mira B. If we do not find deviation from radial symmetry or deviations unrelated to the position of Mira B, this would then mean that the cause for the OH maser flare is more likely due to stellar activity and unrelated to Mira B.</prp:abstract>
